Define X and Y, the TRAIN and TEST dataset¶

In [16]:
array = df1.values
X = array[:,0:6]
Y = array[:,6]
In [17]:
# Split-out test/validation dataset
validation_size = 0.20
seed = 7
X_train, X_validation, Y_train, Y_validation = train_test_split(X, Y,
test_size=validation_size, random_state=seed)

Spot-Check both Linear (Linear, Lasso. and ElasticNet) and Non-Linear(KNeighbors, RegressionTrees and SupportVector) Regression Algorithms¶

In [ ]:
In [18]:
# Set test options and evaluation metric
num_folds = 10
seed = 7
scoring = 'neg_mean_absolute_error'
In [19]:
# Spot-Check Algorithms
models = []
models.append(('LR', LinearRegression()))
models.append(('LASSO', Lasso()))
models.append(('EN', ElasticNet()))
models.append(('KNN', KNeighborsRegressor()))
models.append(('CART', DecisionTreeRegressor()))
models.append(('SVR', SVR()))
In [20]:
# evaluate each model in turn
results = []
names = []
for name, model in models:
    kfold = KFold(n_splits=num_folds, random_state=seed)
    cv_results = cross_val_score(model, X_train, Y_train, cv=kfold, scoring=scoring)
    results.append(cv_results)
    names.append(name)
    msg = "%s: %f (%f)" % (name, cv_results.mean(), cv_results.std())
    print(msg)

Feature Standardization using different scalers followed by spot-checking regression algorithms using sklearn's pipeline feature¶

In [22]:
# Standardize the dataset using StandardScaler. Since the distributions are NOT normal/gaussian, 
#, we do not expect strong improvement/reduction in error, fromt the StandardScaler
pipelines = []
pipelines.append(('ScaledLR', Pipeline([('Scaler', preprocessing.StandardScaler()),('LR',
LinearRegression())])))
pipelines.append(('ScaledLASSO', Pipeline([('Scaler', preprocessing.StandardScaler()),('LASSO',
Lasso())])))
pipelines.append(('ScaledEN', Pipeline([('Scaler', preprocessing.StandardScaler()),('EN',
ElasticNet())])))
pipelines.append(('ScaledKNN', Pipeline([('Scaler', preprocessing.StandardScaler()),('KNN',
KNeighborsRegressor())])))
pipelines.append(('ScaledCART', Pipeline([('Scaler', preprocessing.StandardScaler()),('CART',
DecisionTreeRegressor())])))
pipelines.append(('ScaledSVR', Pipeline([('Scaler', preprocessing.StandardScaler()),('SVR', SVR())])))
results = []
names = []
for name, model in pipelines:
    kfold = KFold(n_splits=num_folds, random_state=seed)
    cv_results = cross_val_score(model, X_train, Y_train, cv=kfold, scoring=scoring)
    results.append(cv_results)
    names.append(name)
    msg = "%s: %f (%f)" % (name, cv_results.mean(), cv_results.std())
    print(msg)

# and makes the distribution more appropriate for this dataset
pipelines = []
pipelines.append(('ScaledLR', Pipeline([('Scaler', preprocessing.RobustScaler()),('LR',
LinearRegression())])))
pipelines.append(('ScaledLASSO', Pipeline([('Scaler', preprocessing.RobustScaler()),('LASSO',
Lasso())])))
pipelines.append(('ScaledEN', Pipeline([('Scaler', preprocessing.RobustScaler()),('EN',
ElasticNet())])))
pipelines.append(('ScaledKNN', Pipeline([('Scaler', preprocessing.RobustScaler()),('KNN',
KNeighborsRegressor())])))
pipelines.append(('ScaledCART', Pipeline([('Scaler', preprocessing.RobustScaler()),('CART',
DecisionTreeRegressor())])))
pipelines.append(('ScaledSVR', Pipeline([('Scaler', preprocessing.RobustScaler()),('SVR', SVR())])))
results = []
names = []
for name, model in pipelines:
    kfold = KFold(n_splits=num_folds, random_state=seed)
    cv_results = cross_val_score(model, X_train, Y_train, cv=kfold, scoring=scoring)
    results.append(cv_results)
    names.append(name)
    msg = "%s: %f (%f)" % (name, cv_results.mean(), cv_results.std())
    print(msg)

# ensembles (b)
ensembles = []
ensembles.append(('ScaledAB', Pipeline([('Scaler', preprocessing.RobustScaler()),('AB',
AdaBoostRegressor())])))
ensembles.append(('ScaledGBM', Pipeline([('Scaler', preprocessing.RobustScaler()),('GBM',
GradientBoostingRegressor())])))
ensembles.append(('ScaledRF', Pipeline([('Scaler', preprocessing.RobustScaler()),('RF',
RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=10))])))
ensembles.append(('ScaledET', Pipeline([('Scaler', preprocessing.RobustScaler()),('ET',
ExtraTreesRegressor(n_estimators=10))])))
results = []
names = []
for name, model in ensembles:
    kfold = KFold(n_splits=num_folds, random_state=seed)
    cv_results = cross_val_score(model, X_train, Y_train, cv=kfold, scoring=scoring)
    results.append(cv_results)
    names.append(name)
    msg = "%s: %f (%f)" % (name, cv_results.mean(), cv_results.std())
    print(msg)

Evaluation¶

The final-tuned algorithm yielded an error of 4.72 as compared to 6.03 for the untuned/unscaled dataset - this represents a ~26 % reduction in the error.

Summary¶

  1. Data Exploration - Dataset loading and data integrity Check, Correlation Statistics/Matrix to identify interactions between variables, Histograms to identify feature distributions (skewed, normal, tail-lenghts, etc.) was completed in this section.
  2. Spot-Check Algorithms - KNN had the best performance (dataset was not standardized at this point). Mean absolute error was noted to be 5.97.
  3. Spot-Check Algorithms on Standardized Dataset - Out of the scaling techniques evaluated, KNN continued to exhibit the best performance. Error was noted to decrease from 5.97 to 5.57.
  4. Algorithm Tuning - This did not have as much of an impact and the error remained at 5.57.
  5. Ensemble Method - From the four(4) combined Bagging and Boosting Algorithms to further improve the regression model, RandomForest had the best performance, where the error dropped from 5.57 to 5.12.
  6. Ensemble Tuning was used to further improve the performance of the model, and it did. The mean absolute error was reduced from 5.12 to 4.88
  7. Finally, the test/validation dataset that was held out, was fitted to the tuned model, and yielded an error of 4.72.

Overall, the analysis clearly showed an improvement in the predictive performance of the model, however, the model is noted to not be strong enough. The following could help yield a better model for the dataset:

  1. Column/feature specific transformation
  2. Better feature selection by the dataset providers - this dataset, for being a housing dataset, is obviously lacking in critical details/factors, such as the number of bedrooms, the overall square footage, etc., thereby limiting the extent of the predictive model built.
